LESSON 5: MATPLOTLIB INTRODUCTION

1. Overall introduction

Matplotlib is an open-source Python library for data visualization.
Matplotlib is the whole package. And it contains 2 modules: pylab and pyplot.

  • pyplot provides the state-machine interface for plotting. That means, each line of code change the state of plotting.
  • pylab can be said as the combination of numpy functionality and pyplot functionality.

2. Install and import libraries

Install matplotlib by running this command in jupyter notebook: !conda install -c conda-forge matplotlib -y

Change line color by color or c

List of colors here

In[11]:
# Using `color`
plt.plot(x, np.sin(x - 0), color='blue')        # Color by name
plt.plot(x, np.sin(x - 1), color='g')           # Color by shortname
plt.plot(x, np.sin(x - 2), color='0.75')        # Grayscale between 0 and 1
plt.plot(x, np.sin(x - 3), color='#FFDD44')     # Hex code (RRGGBB from 00 to FF)
plt.plot(x, np.sin(x - 4), color=(1.0,0.2,0.3)) # RGB tuple, values 0 to 1
plt.show()
In[12]:

Change line format by Format String

Format String = '[marker][line][color]'

In[21]:
plt.plot(x, x + 0, '-g')    # [no marker][solid][green]
plt.plot(x, x + 2, 'o--c')  # [circle][dashed][cyan] 
plt.plot(x, x + 4, 's-.k')  # [square][dashdot][black]
plt.show()

Bubble plot

Bubble plot is Scatter plot with multiple sizes of scatter

In[25]:
color_map = np.arange(50)
bubble_size = np.random.randint(1, 200, size=50)

plt.scatter(x, y, s=bubble_size, c=color_map, cmap='viridis')
plt.colorbar()
plt.show()

3.6. Histogram

A histogram is an approximate representation of the distribution of numerical data.

In[6]:
y = np.random.normal(200, 1000, 5000)

plt.hist(y)
plt.show()
In[43]:
yy = np.random.uniform(-100, 100, 5000)

plt.hist(yy)
plt.show()
In[7]:
# Some additional arguments for histogram
plt.hist(y,                 # data
         bins=50,           # number of bar        
         alpha=0.5,         # opacity
         color='green',     # bar color
         edgecolor='black') # edge of bar color
plt.show()

4.4. All title, label and legend

In[49]:
plt.bar(index-0.2, value_1, width=0.2, label='cat_1')

plt.bar(index+0.2, value_3, width=0.2, label='cat_3')
plt.legend(loc='upper right')
plt.xlabel("Category")
plt.ylabel("Value")
plt.title("This is my figure")
plt.show()

4.5. Add text

In[50]:
plt.hist(y,                 # data
         bins=50,           # number of bar        
         alpha=0.5,         # opacity
         color='green',     # bar color
         edgecolor='black') # edge of bar color
plt.text(-420, 275, 'Normal distribution')
plt.show()

4.6. Annotate figure

In[51]:
plt.hist(y,                 # data
         bins=50,           # number of bar        
         alpha=0.5,         # opacity
         color='green',     # bar color
         edgecolor='black') # edge of bar color
plt.annotate('mean',
             xytext=(100, 270),
             xy=(-100, 250),
             arrowprops=dict(facecolor='black'))
plt.show()

5. Axes limit in plt.plot() or plt.hist()

5.1. Using plt.xlim() and plt.ylim()

Normal plot

In[52]:
plt.plot(x, np.sin(x))
plt.show()

With plt.xlim() and plt.ylim()

In[53]:
plt.plot(x, np.sin(x))
plt.xlim(-1, 11)
plt.ylim(-1.5, 1.5)
plt.show()

Reverse the axis

In[54]:
plt.plot(x, np.sin(x))

plt.xlim(-1, 11)
plt.ylim(1.5, -1.5)
plt.show()

With plt.hist()

In[55]:
plt.hist(y,                 # data
         bins=50,           # number of bar        
         alpha=0.5,         # opacity
         color='green',     # bar color
         edgecolor='black') # edge of bar color
plt.show()
In[56]:
plt.hist(y,                 # data
         bins=50,           # number of bar        
         alpha=0.5,         # opacity
         color='green',     # bar color
         edgecolor='black') # edge of bar color
plt.xlim(-300, 110)
plt.show()

5.2. Limit axes by plt.axis()

In[57]:
plt.plot(x, np.sin(x))
plt.axis([-1, 11, -1.5, 1.5])
plt.show()

5.3. Automatically limit axis

In[58]:
plt.plot(x, np.sin(x))
plt.axis('equal') # ensure aspect ratio
plt.show()

6. Subplots - Multiple plots

6.1. Create single sub-plot by plt.subplot()

In[13]:
for subplot_index in range(4):
    plt.subplot(2, 2, subplot_index+1)
    plt.text(0.5, 0.5, f'subplot_index_{subplot_index}', fontsize=12, horizontalalignment='center')

# Add space between subplots
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

6.2. Create the whole sub-plots by plt.subplots()

In[60]:
num_rows, num_cols = 3, 2
fig, ax = plt.subplots(num_rows, num_cols)

for row_index in range(num_rows):
    for col_index in range(num_cols):
        ax[row_index, col_index].text(
            0.5, 0.5, f'subplot_index_{row_index}_{col_index}', fontsize=12, horizontalalignment='center')

# Add space between subplots
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

6.3. More specific subplots by using plt.GridSpec()

In[61]:
grid = plt.GridSpec(3, 3)

plt.subplot(grid[0, 0])
plt.subplot(grid[0, 1:])
plt.subplot(grid[1:, :2])
plt.subplot(grid[1:, 2])
# Add space between subplots
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

6.4. Multiple plots in one figure by twinx()

In[62]:
x = np.linspace(-5, 5, 50)
In[63]:
fig, ax_1 = plt.subplots()

ax_1.plot(x, np.sin(x), label='sin(x)')
ax_1.set_ylabel('sin(x)')

ax_2 = ax_1.twinx()
ax_2.plot(x, np.exp(x), 'r.-', label='exp(x)')
ax_2.set_ylabel('exp(x)')

fig.legend(loc='upper left')
plt.show()
In[64]:
x = np.arange(1, 11)
y = np.random.randint(0, 100, 10)
z = np.random.randint(0, 100, 10)
In[65]:
fig, ax_1 = plt.subplots()

ax_1.bar(x, y, label='y_value')
ax_1.set_ylabel('y_value')

ax_2 = ax_1.twinx()
ax_2.plot(x, z, 'r.-', label='z_value')
ax_2.set_ylabel('z_value')

fig.legend(loc='upper left')
plt.show()

Note:

  • We use the daily historical sales data from previous lecture in this homework. (Use this link to download this dataset)
  • All figures must have title, label and legend.

7.1. Exercise 1:

Randomly choose 3 shops, use one line plot figure to show the total turnover of them each month over 34 months (from January 2013 is 0, February 2013 is 1,..., October 2015 is 33.)

7.2. Exercise 2:

Randomly choose 1 item, use one combo figure with bar plot and line plot to show the sales and the turnover of it over 34 months (from January 2013 is 0, February 2013 is 1,..., October 2015 is 33.)

7.3. Exercise 3:

Randomly choose 3 items, use one bar plot figure to show the sales of them in 3 years 2013, 2014, and 2015.

7.4. Exercise 4:

Randomly choose 1 shop, use stack plot figure to show the contribution of turnover of each item each month over 34 months (from January 2013 is 0, February 2013 is 1,..., October 2015 is 33.)

7.5. Exercise 5:

Randomly choose 1 shop, use pie plot figure to show the contribution of turnover (in percent) of each item in 3 years 2013, 2014, and 2015. (1 pie plot figure for each year, use subplots to put all 3 figures together)

7.6. Exercise 6:

Randomly choose 1 item, use histogram figure to show the distribution of sales of the item over 34 months (from January 2013 is 0, February 2013 is 1,..., October 2015 is 33.)
